{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521827"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:37:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:37:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13760"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13760"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.05,0.52,0.05,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6379"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108349"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6379"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13760"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90739"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"417"},{"type":"tags","id":"3975"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12305"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12307"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12308"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14784"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18645"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108349"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman is admitted to hospital following an open cholecystectomy earlier today. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears uncomfortable at rest. Her pulse rate is 105/min, blood pressure 155/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 91% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. She reports her abdominal pain score as 8/10 at rest and 10/10 on movement. She is unable to take deep breaths or cough effectively due to severe incisional pain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate method to assess the need for increasing analgesia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pain score at rest","Systolic blood pressure","Ability to cough and take deep breaths","Oxygen saturation","Heart rate"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the postoperative setting, assessment of functional ability, such as the \u003Cstrong\u003Eability to cough and take deep breaths\u003C/strong\u003E, is a better guide for titrating analgesia than relying on pain scores alone. Pain scores are very subjective and variable as the pain threshold and tolerance will vary from patient to patient. Moreover, relying solely on pain scores to guide opioid titration is known to increase the risk of opioid-induced ventilatory impairment, as some patients may report higher pain scores due to factors such as anxiety, catastrophising, chronic pain, or opioid tolerance. Conversely, some patients may under-report their pain due to stoicism or cultural factors, or because they only experience significant pain with movement, deep breathing, or coughing rather than at rest. Inadequate analgesia can lead to splinting, atelectasis, and increased risk of respiratory complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPain score at rest\u003C/strong\u003E alone is insufficient to guide analgesia titration. A patient may report low pain scores at rest but still have inadequate analgesia for functional recovery, as pain often increases significantly with movement or respiratory effort.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eheart rate\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Esystolic blood pressure\u003C/strong\u003E can be elevated in the setting of pain, they are non-specific signs that can be affected by many other factors in the post-operative period such as hypovolaemia, medications, or pre-existing conditions. Using vital signs alone to guide opioid titration can lead to over- or under-treatment of pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly, while pain can sometimes cause a decreased \u003Cstrong\u003Eoxygen saturation\u003C/strong\u003E due to splinting and atelectasis, using this parameter alone to guide opioid titration is not reliable, as over-sedation from opioids can also lead to hypoxaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principle in post-operative pain management is to achieve adequate analgesia that allows for early mobilisation, deep breathing, and effective coughing. This approach not only manages pain but also helps prevent post-operative complications such as pneumonia and deep vein thrombosis. Therefore, assessing the patient\u0027s ability to perform these functions is crucial in determining the adequacy of pain control and the need for adjusting analgesia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Assessment of functional ability is a better guide for titrating analgesia than pain scores alone in the post-operative setting.","Relying on pain scores alone to guide opioid titration can lead to over-sedation and opioid-induced ventilatory impairment.","Patients may under-report pain due to stoicism or because pain only occurs with movement, deep breathing, or coughing."],"references":["PS41 (G) position statement on acute pain management. In: Australian and New Zealand College of Anaesthetists (ANZCA) and Faculty of Pain Medicine [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.anzca.edu.au/getattachment/558316c5-ea93-457c-b51f-d57556b0ffa7/PS41(G)-Position-statement-on-acute-pain-management-2023#page=","Opioid Analgesic Stewardship in Acute Pain Clinical Care Standard - Acute care edition. In: Australian Commission on Safety and Quality in Health Care. 2022. Available at: https://www.safetyandquality.gov.au/sites/default/files/2022-04/opioid-analgesic-stewardship-in-acute-pain-clinical-care-standard.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90739"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13760"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90739"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-09T18:15:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-09T18:16:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6379"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108349"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"re